{"id":"1507.06265","submitter":"Stefan G\\\"uttel","authors":"Vladimir Druskin, Stefan G\\\"uttel, Leonid Knizhnerman","title":"Near-optimal perfectly matched layers for indefinite Helmholtz problems","comments":"Accepted for publication in SIAM Review. To appear 2016","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"MIMS Preprint 2013.53, Manchester Institute for Mathematics\n  Sciences, The University of Manchester, United Kingdom","categories":"math.NA math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A new construction of an absorbing boundary condition for indefinite\nHelmholtz problems on unbounded domains is presented. This construction is\nbased on a near-best uniform rational interpolant of the inverse square root\nfunction on the union of a negative and positive real interval, designed with\nthe help of a classical result by Zolotarev. Using Krein's interpretation of a\nStieltjes continued fraction, this interpolant can be converted into a\nthree-term finite difference discretization of a perfectly matched layer (PML)\nwhich converges exponentially fast in the number of grid points. The\nconvergence rate is asymptotically optimal for both propagative and evanescent\nwave modes. Several numerical experiments and illustrations are included.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 22 Jul 2015 17:37:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-07-23"}
