{"id":"1507.06513","submitter":"Gregory Puleo","authors":"Thomas Mahoney, Gregory J. Puleo, Douglas B. West","title":"Online Paintability: The Slow-Coloring Game","comments":"18 pages. Revised introduction, restructured several proofs","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The slow-coloring game is played by Lister and Painter on a graph $G$. On\neach round, Lister marks a nonempty subset $M$ of the uncolored vertices,\nscoring $|M|$ points. Painter then gives a color to a subset of $M$ that is\nindependent in $G$. The game ends when all vertices are colored. Painter and\nLister want to minimize and maximize the total score, respectively. The best\nscore that each player can guarantee is the sum-color cost of $G$, written\n$\\mathring{\\mathrm{s}}(G)$. The game is an online variant of online sum list\ncoloring.\n  We proe $\\frac{|V(G)|}{2\\alpha(G)} + \\frac{1}{2} \\leq\n\\frac{\\mathring{\\mathrm{s}}(G)}{|V(G)|} \\leq \\max\\left\\{\n\\frac{|V(H)|}{\\alpha(H)} : H \\subset G\\right\\}$, where $\\alpha(G)$ is the\nindependence number, and we study when equality holds in the bounds. We compute\n$\\mathring{\\mathrm{s}}(G)$ for graphs with $\\alpha(G) = 2$. Among $n$-vertex\ngraphs, we prove that $\\mathring{\\mathrm{s}}$ is minimized by the star and\nmaximized by the path. We also obtain good bounds on\n$\\mathring{\\mathrm{s}}(K_{r,s})$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 23 Jul 2015 14:32:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 5 Jul 2017 21:37:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-07"}
